Introduction

In this report, we look into analyzing how people vote on gaming legalization in different US counties, using a detailed dataset of 1287 records. This data includes key information like population, income, and how many people are for or against gaming. We've applied three main machine learning techniques—Decision Trees, Naïve Bayes, and K-Nearest Neighbors—to predict voting outcomes, ensuring our approach is solid by preprocessing data and selecting relevant variables.

Prepping the data was key, as we had to make sure everything was in the right format and only included useful information for our predictions. Our goal with this analysis is to shed light on what drives voting behavior on this issue and provide valuable insights into the mix of economic, demographic, and social factors that influence these decisions. This concise journey through data analysis to prediction showcases our methodical approach to understanding gaming legalization votes in a political data science context.

The data is balanced as it is distributed amlost equally between both category. If the data was not balances then handling it involves resampling methods like oversampling or undersampling to equalize class representation, or generating synthetic examples via SMOTE to enhance minority class presence. Adjusting algorithm parameters, employing ensemble methods, and using nuanced evaluation metrics like Precision, Recall, and F1 Score can also help mitigate bias towards dominant classes. In extreme imbalances, treating the problem as anomaly detection may offer a unique solution. The choice of strategy should align with the dataset's specifics and the analytical objectives, ensuring a balanced approach to model accuracy and class representation.

# Fit the models on the training set

nb.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set

y_pred_nb = nb.predict(X_test)
y_pred_knn = knn.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy for each model
accuracy_dt = accuracy_score(Y_test, y_pred_dt)
accuracy_nb = accuracy_score(Y_test, y_pred_nb)
accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(Y_test, y_pred_knn)

# Calculate sensitivity (recall) for each model, specifying 'Yes' as the positive class
recall_dt = recall_score(Y_test, y_pred_dt, pos_label='Yes')
recall_nb = recall_score(Y_test, y_pred_nb, pos_label='Yes')
recall_knn = recall_score(Y_test, y_pred_knn, pos_label='Yes')
